     "], {{0, 1306}, {1936, 0}}, {0, 255},
     ColorFunction->RGBColor],
    BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSize->{617.1812500000001, Automatic},
   ImageSizeRaw->{1936, 1306},
   PlotRange->{{0, 1936}, {0, 1306}}]], "Text",ExpressionUUID->
  "3f7a7410-de0f-489e-8b96-7143a9d5a71c"],
 "\n\t\t",
 StyleBox["Figure Gaussian Beam Parameters:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " The figure shows the beam at the input plane, output plane, the phase \n\t\
\t\t\t\tat the output plane and the wave sampled along the z-axis.\n",
 StyleBox["\n1) Ensure that the beam size at the output of your simulation is \
",
  FontSize->13],
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SqrtBox["2"], 
   SubscriptBox["w", "0"]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f060ea92-e898-485f-9fae-4b348936a338"],
 "\n",
 StyleBox["2) Ensure that the wave-front curvature is ",
  FontSize->13],
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"R", "=", 
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SubscriptBox["z", "R"]}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2ed3c08f-97e1-4e9a-879e-24e4b3afb145"],
 ". There are various ways to accomplish this but you may find the unwrap \
command very useful here.",
 StyleBox["\n3) Using the results of your simulation argue what the Gouy \
phase is and how you determined it.\n4) Make an additional plot through the \
x-z plane to show the diverging Gaussian beam like in ",
  FontSize->13],
 StyleBox["Figure: Gaussian beam diagram",
  FontSize->13,
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 StyleBox[" from above",
  FontSize->13]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.760653317870872*^9, 3.760653379482809*^9}, {
  3.76065343862327*^9, 3.760653498432395*^9}, {3.760654097147524*^9, 
  3.76065411177414*^9}, {3.760658169015182*^9, 3.7606582467566967`*^9}, {
  3.7606626620610027`*^9, 3.7606627671285887`*^9}, {3.760664168343039*^9, 
  3.760664208806808*^9}, {3.760664353676653*^9, 3.7606643569689617`*^9}, {
  3.7606665078427353`*^9, 3.760666518907428*^9}, {3.7607532851045017`*^9, 
  3.760753294367056*^9}, {3.913054496562681*^9, 3.913054498162472*^9}},
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.87, 0.94, 1],ExpressionUUID->"904dc57d-8879-4a54-b799-38ea011713f4"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["1.2 Arago spot simulation",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76063845290236*^9, 3.7606384588721457`*^9}, {
   3.7606384926578608`*^9, 3.760638504807088*^9}, {3.7606412761792727`*^9, 
   3.760641281290709*^9}, {3.760642824870195*^9, 3.7606428256086187`*^9}, {
   3.760656070378839*^9, 3.7606560818220873`*^9}, 3.76065828147358*^9, {
   3.760658361575371*^9, 3.760658367528493*^9}, {3.760658425784643*^9, 
   3.760658426716951*^9}, {3.760662786421422*^9, 3.760662790749858*^9}, {
   3.760663025485414*^9, 3.760663025598763*^9}, 3.760667301383237*^9},
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"060e157e-c236-40bf-a54a-7cbc8ecf97c4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Introduction: ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "We spoke in class about the spot of Arago. I showed my simulation of this \
phenomenon. Now it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s your turn to reproduce this fascinating \
experiment in simulation!\n",
 StyleBox["\nInstructions:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " ",
 StyleBox["Make a, ",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 StyleBox["3D",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0],
  Background->RGBColor[1, 0.9, 0.8]],
 StyleBox[" grid of points in order to design the index profile of the sphere \
with Nx = Ny = 256 and Nz = 512 pixels, \[Lambda] = 4 \[Mu]m, radius of the \
sphere will be r0 = 10\[Mu]m the maximum extent of the transverse grid should \
be 20*r0. Your input wave should propagate zMax = 10*r0. The input wave is \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]1\[CloseCurlyQuote] sampled across z = 0. ",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 "Your program should display the physical extent of the simulation grid to \
the command window for reference. In order to sample the input wave (which is \
1) you should also make a ",
 StyleBox["2D grid of points with Nx = Ny = 256 with the same physical \
parameters as the 3D grid. ",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 "To simulate an opaque sphere like the one below you should choose a large \
imaginary component to the index of refraction."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.760658479059244*^9, 3.760658537735942*^9}, 
