Cell[TextData[StyleBox["1.3 Coupling light into a hollow fiber",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76063845290236*^9, 3.7606384588721457`*^9}, {
   3.7606384926578608`*^9, 3.760638504807088*^9}, {3.7606412761792727`*^9, 
   3.760641281290709*^9}, {3.760642824870195*^9, 3.7606428256086187`*^9}, {
   3.760656070378839*^9, 3.7606560818220873`*^9}, 3.76065828147358*^9, {
   3.760658361575371*^9, 3.760658367528493*^9}, {3.760658425784643*^9, 
   3.760658426716951*^9}, {3.760662786421422*^9, 3.760662790749858*^9}, {
   3.760663025485414*^9, 3.760663025598763*^9}, {3.760664071001439*^9, 
   3.760664078392292*^9}, {3.760667304121553*^9, 3.7606673041938963`*^9}},
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"22791031-355b-452c-ba27-eaf8e0e05c4f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Introduction: ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "One very important application area is coupling light into optical \
waveguides (think telecom industry). In this example we will explore coupling \
a Gaussian beam into a hollow waveguide. The 3D waveguide will be composed of \
concentric cylinders with the interior vacuum and the outer cylinder having \
index of refraction ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"n", "=", "1.45"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c5637720-933e-4185-8741-cedd2eab109a"],
 " (the interior of the cylinder will be vacuum so n=1). Your task is to \
focus an input Gaussian beam into the open portion of the hollow capillary.\n",
 StyleBox["\nInstructions:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " ",
 StyleBox["Make a, 3D grid of points in order to design the index profile of \
the hollow capillary with Nx = Ny = 128 and Nz = 1024 pixels, \[Lambda] = 4 \
\[Mu]m, the inner radius of the capillary will be ri = 10\[Mu]m and the outer \
radius will be ro = 4\[Times]ri. The maximum extent of the transverse grid \
should be 10*ri. Your input wave should propagate zMax = 15*ri. Also make a \
2D grid of points with Nx = Ny = 256 with the same physical parameters as the \
3D grid to sample the input wave, which will be a Gaussian beam with radius \
w0 and wavefront radius R BOTH OF WHICH YOU WILL DETERMINE TO BE OPTIMAL for \
coupling light into the fiber. Optimal coupling means as little loss as \
possible i.e., coupling as much light into the fiber as possible. It will be \
best to specify w0 in terms of the inner radius i.e., w0 = \
\[Alpha]\[Times]ri, where 0 \[LessEqual] \[Alpha] \[LessEqual] 1. HINT: the \
beam is focused at the fiber input, which completely determines R for a given \
w0.",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 "\n\nProvide an image like the one below:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.760658479059244*^9, 3.760658537735942*^9}, 
   3.760662492225428*^9, {3.760663039373623*^9, 3.760663061372621*^9}, {
   3.760663125169982*^9, 3.760663125584721*^9}, {3.7606631663947067`*^9, 
   3.760663257414106*^9}, {3.7606636125739317`*^9, 3.760663667172974*^9}, {
   3.760663862549348*^9, 3.760663922468251*^9}, {3.760663974613756*^9, 
   3.760664001299012*^9}, {3.7606640805974827`*^9, 3.760664083859085*^9}, {
   3.760664961718923*^9, 3.760664982231196*^9}, {3.760666584501575*^9, 
   3.760666739761511*^9}, {3.7606668256858177`*^9, 3.7606668261535463`*^9}, {
   3.7606675643887873`*^9, 3.760667675808729*^9}, {3.7606677494722157`*^9, 
   3.7606677918332653`*^9}, {3.76066783249662*^9, 3.760667993491968*^9}, {
   3.760668268712144*^9, 3.760668298272973*^9}, {3.7606683445080433`*^9, 
   3.760668346144477*^9}, {3.76066838485625*^9, 3.7606684069856977`*^9}, {
   3.760669677821866*^9, 
   3.760669696510049*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"74b3c8fe-1cdd-4564-94cd-\
5df160d05076"],

