   ImageSize->{683.596875, Automatic},
   ImageSizeRaw->{2035, 986},
   PlotRange->{{0, 2035}, {0, 986}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->
  "7db636f4-5b35-4b14-9307-b35808fe2929"],
 "\n\t\t\t\t",
 StyleBox["Figure 4-f imaging system",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ": Important features include (1) input plane field, (2) transmission \
function of lens 1 \n\t\t\t\t(3) focal plane of lens 1 i.e., the spatial \
filter plane (4) transmission function of lens 2 (5) output field plane."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.760638400661853*^9, 3.7606384480095167`*^9}, {
  3.7606412470798798`*^9, 3.760641267432078*^9}, {3.760644080013381*^9, 
  3.7606440982036552`*^9}, {3.760644826938789*^9, 3.760644835381258*^9}, {
  3.760663314739203*^9, 
  3.760663317586854*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6567d498-8c37-43f1-8a26-\
287a64491484"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["2.1 A spatial filter for laser beams",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76063845290236*^9, 3.7606384588721457`*^9}, {
  3.7606384926578608`*^9, 3.760638504807088*^9}, {3.7606412761792727`*^9, 
  3.760641281290709*^9}, {3.760642824870195*^9, 3.7606428256086187`*^9}},
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"558598f8-6be2-4d23-a32f-156e5fffff66"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Introduction: ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Many applications such as imaging, require a very smooth beam profile. That \
is, the shape of the laser beam when viewed across a plane transverse to its \
propagation direction must be well approximated by a Gaussian amplitude. It \
is often not possible to produce a perfect Gaussian shape directly from a \
laser source for various reasons, so one very useful tool is a spatial \
filter. The idea is to use the concepts of Fourier optics to transform the \
input wave into its Angular Spectrum and then remove high spatial frequency \
components via a low pass spatial filter.\n",
 StyleBox["\nInstructions:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " ",
 StyleBox["Make an isotropic, 2D grid of points with N = 1024 pixels, a pixel \
size of \[DifferentialD]x=10\[Mu]m, and \[Lambda] = 0.532 \[Mu]m. Make the \
lens diameter 6 mm.",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 " Your program should display the physical extent of the simulation grid to \
the command window for reference. Note that with the parameters given, the \
simulation grid is quite small in terms of real units. However, the systems \
modeled in these exercises are appropriate for many experimental \
configurations such as bio-imaging.\n\nBecause the project will rely on \
lenses we must calculate the minimum focal length that can be used in our \
simulated system. The physical idea behind this calculation is very \
straightforward: in the case that we illuminate a simulated lens with a unit \
amplitude plane wave, we must ensure that the focal spot (diameter) not be \
smaller than one pixel. This ensures that the phase of the lens is well \
sampled on our grid. For our purposes it is useful to approximate the input \
as a Gaussian beam and write\n\n\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"w", "(", "f", ")"}], "2"], " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["w", "0", "2"], "(", 
     RowBox[{"1", "+", 
      FractionBox[
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["f", "2"], " ", 
        SuperscriptBox["\[Lambda]", "2"]}], 
       RowBox[{
        SuperscriptBox["\[Pi]", "2"], 
        SubsuperscriptBox["w", "0", "4"]}]]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"9e4da3e6-1a7e-4bcd-82a0-ee8b63df04a2"],
 "\n\nthen, solving for the focal length, which we take to be positive\n\n\t\
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"f", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["z", "R"], 
     FractionBox[
      RowBox[{"w", "(", "f", ")"}], 
      SubscriptBox["w", "0"]], 
     SqrtBox[
      RowBox[{"1", " ", "-", 
       FractionBox[
        SubsuperscriptBox["w", "0", "2"], 
        SuperscriptBox[
         RowBox[{"w", "(", "f", ")"}], "2"]]}]]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"527cad60-2d64-49a7-a204-2983282b9e9d"],
 "\n\nIn this expression we set ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"w", "(", "f", ")"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a68fc9ba-e222-4c91-b6c8-974de019c7fd"],
 " equal to the radius of the lens and take ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["w", "0"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0b292fcd-8a0e-4a69-9e20-3a60e5cce522"],
 " to be the characteristic radius of the focused wave. Then the minimum \
focal length that can be used in the simulation is\n\n\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["f", "Min"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"2", 
     SubscriptBox["z", "R"], 
     FractionBox[
      SubscriptBox["R", "Lens"], 
      RowBox[{"\[DifferentialD]", "x"}]], 
     SqrtBox[
      RowBox[{"1", " ", "-", 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"\[DifferentialD]", 
         SuperscriptBox["x", "2"]}], 
        RowBox[{"4", 
         SubsuperscriptBox["R", "Lens", "2"]}]]}]]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"443f2786-8655-496a-bc99-bdc5dcc7fdcf"],
 "\n\nNote that we could have also calculated the width of the central lobe \
of the Jinc function that would have resulted after the wave was focused \
through the lens aperture.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Now, construct a spherical lens transmission function in the \
paraxial limit with radius of 3 mm.",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 " This will be used at least twice in this portion of the project alone, so \
it is best to define this outside of any loops. Sample and input Gaussian \
beam whose radius, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["w", "in"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4aacdde4-e50f-41ba-b4b7-f8c0d4063fc5"],
 " is 1/10 the grid extent. This portion of the project is an exercise in \
spatial filtering, so we will simulate a non-uniform beam profile in a few \
ways and see how we can filter out the non-uniformity.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Construct a 4-f imaging system (refer to the Figure 4-f imaging \
system above):",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 "\n1) The input wave (the field sampled along the input plane) is propagated \
through free space a distance ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["f", "1"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "13486bea-1d83-46e5-ac22-39ce08ac31e2"],
 " to lens plane 1\n2) The transmission function of lens 1 is applied to the \
field at lens plane 1\n3) The field is propagated through free space a \
distance ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["f", "1"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "29996ef2-8b3b-4493-a8ff-4b1d90ffe69b"],
 " to the focal plane of lens 1 (focal plane)\n4) A spatial filter is applied \
at the focal plane\n5) The field after the spatial filter is propagated \
through free space a distance ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["f", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5ca5b913-35a0-41b6-a362-5c96abd4483a"],
 " to the second lens (lens plane 2)\n6) The transmission function of lens 2 \
is applied to the field at lens plane 2\n7) The field after lens 2 is \
propagated through free space a distance ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["f", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "724548b5-783f-4397-9e48-69b95483015e"],
 " to the output plane"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.760638497025454*^9, 3.7606387109031763`*^9}, {
   3.760638773508862*^9, 3.760638921406715*^9}, {3.760639934045269*^9, 
   3.7606400305997334`*^9}, {3.760640198057116*^9, 3.760640352383135*^9}, {
   3.76064043844053*^9, 3.7606408225225067`*^9}, {3.760640985912714*^9, 
   3.760641078862088*^9}, {3.7606411772134447`*^9, 3.760641177994688*^9}, {
   3.760641304604528*^9, 3.760641345497612*^9}, {3.7606413997532263`*^9, 
   3.7606414937396193`*^9}, {3.760641525196196*^9, 3.7606416581385317`*^9}, {
   3.7606417255900173`*^9, 3.760641796895686*^9}, {3.760641837052301*^9, 
   3.760641850660589*^9}, {3.7606418864516783`*^9, 3.760641916580336*^9}, {
   3.760641972092001*^9, 3.7606422902323236`*^9}, {3.760642362428143*^9, 
   3.760642392908657*^9}, {3.760642835028245*^9, 3.7606428361774473`*^9}, {
   3.760642889154009*^9, 3.760642916095335*^9}, {3.760643207443725*^9, 
   3.7606432170864687`*^9}, {3.76064412944522*^9, 3.7606441346889267`*^9}, {
   3.7606459554224787`*^9, 3.760645962220704*^9}, {3.760655481288361*^9, 
   3.760655497075527*^9}, {3.760657781741878*^9, 3.760657793920895*^9}, 
   3.760662512993951*^9},ExpressionUUID->"5894a609-84dd-40c9-bf23-\
7d5cd2015a0e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 StyleBox["2.1.1 Construct and investigate the effects of a low pass filter \
on the modulated beam profile",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\tModulate the input beam with a unit amplitude, non-negative cosine \
grating with frequency ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["f", "mod"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"6", "/", 
     SubscriptBox["w", "in"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b932ca25-5908-451a-885f-75c9db4fcd79"],
 " applied in both the x- and y-direction\n\tConstruct and apply a unit \
amplitude, (top-hat) circular spatial filter with a cutoff frequency large \
enough to pass the DC peak but small enough to filter out the modulation"
}], "Text",
