     "], {{0, 1228}, {2132, 0}}, {0, 255},
     ColorFunction->RGBColor],
    BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSize->{859.6890625000001, Automatic},
   ImageSizeRaw->{2132, 1228},
   PlotRange->{{0, 2132}, {0, 1228}}]], "Text",
  Background->None,ExpressionUUID->"1ab3817c-741a-4eb2-9262-d17f0a2bbfe4"],
 "\nThe plot must include appropriate axes labels and show the field at each \
of the planes described in the ",
 StyleBox["Figure 4-f imaging system",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 " figure above. The last panel is the difference between the filtered beam \
and the input beam before modulation.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Answer the following questions about this system:",
  FontSize->13,
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n1) What is the cutoff frequency of the spatial filter necessary to remove \
the side-lobes from the modulation?\n2) Calculate the cutoff frequency \
analytically using Gaussian beam mechanics and report the value you found.\n\
3) Repeat this process using a ",
 StyleBox["CIRCULAR",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["4", "th"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6325f736-f9f3-4575-967e-4c14115a65f1"],
 "-order super-Gaussian filter with the same width as the top-hat filter and \
compare your results using the error. Which has lower error? Include a plot \
like the one above for this case.\n4) Now lower the modulation frequency to \
20% of its initial value. Are you able to filter the modulation in the \
Fourier plane? Which filter has the lowest error? The point here is to \
compare top-hat and super-Gaussian filters with the same width to see which, \
if either, is better."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.760644281426065*^9, 3.7606442936386967`*^9}, {
  3.760644338860169*^9, 3.760644352515818*^9}, {3.760644383773147*^9, 
  3.7606444421454477`*^9}, {3.760644486395708*^9, 3.7606446040376987`*^9}, {
  3.7606447205758743`*^9, 3.760644747129322*^9}, {3.760644897037017*^9, 
  3.76064494987328*^9}, {3.7606452461313257`*^9, 3.760645251341976*^9}, {
  3.7606454290067177`*^9, 3.760645467416404*^9}, {3.7606455205772667`*^9, 
  3.760645530057835*^9}, {3.76064578524361*^9, 3.760645792606056*^9}, {
  3.760653813136623*^9, 3.760653861630962*^9}},
 Background->RGBColor[
  0.87, 0.94, 1],ExpressionUUID->"1fa01579-400c-4003-af4e-05a6d741cd70"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["2.2 Spatial filtering for image processing",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76063845290236*^9, 3.7606384588721457`*^9}, {
  3.7606384926578608`*^9, 3.760638504807088*^9}, {3.7606412761792727`*^9, 
  3.760641281290709*^9}, {3.760642824870195*^9, 3.7606428256086187`*^9}, {
  3.760650805612988*^9, 3.7606508143310213`*^9}},
 FontSize->14,
 FontWeight->"Regular",ExpressionUUID->"7dbbe689-d142-4739-856a-be7596c33b86"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Introduction: ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Many applications in image processing utilize various Fourier filtering \
techniques. Some of these include image blurring, edge finding, band-pass \
filtering etc. In this exercise you will use your 4-f imaging system to \
perform various Fourier filtering techniques on images. For this portion of \
the project, we will be using Matlab\[CloseCurlyQuote]s built in image \
library. Specifically, you can find a test pattern consisting of a Siemens \
star located at: [matlabroot,",
 StyleBox["\[CloseCurlyQuote]/toolbox/images/imdata/testpat1.png\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]]",
  FontColor->RGBColor[
   0.6274509803921569, 0.12549019607843137`, 0.9411764705882353]],
 ". The file path is formatted for a mac machine and is easily modified for \
pc. The Siemens star is particularly nice for image processing because the \
resolution necessary to image this pattern becomes more demanding \
symmetrically near the center. An example of a Siemens star is shown below:\n\
