  "6f67e5c5-862a-4b37-9651-319c05ab0b95"],
 "\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t",
 StyleBox["Figure Siemens star:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Features become finer as r \[Rule] 0\n\nIn this portion of the project you \
will investigate the effects of several Fourier filtering techniques via your \
4-f imaging system. All of the filtering will be applied at the focus, in \
between the two lenses. In this part of the project, we will use larger \
lenses i.e., ",
 StyleBox["make your lens diameter 12 mm.",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 "\n\n",
 StyleBox["Instructions:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Import the Siemens star image using imread(fullpath), then convert it to a \
double using double(). Resize the image using Matlab\[CloseCurlyQuote]s built \
in imresize function so that it contains the same number of pixels as your \
grid. Next, rotate the image using Matlab\[CloseCurlyQuote]s imrotate \
function. Once imported, resized, and rotated, this will be the transmission \
function input to your 4-f imaging system. In addition to resizing and \
rotating your image, set part of the Siemens star to zero so that it is \
easier to see any asymmetry. I suggest something like:\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  GraphicsBox[
   TagBox[RasterBox[CompressedData["
